May be an illustration of text that says 'Betty Robinson Among the stars of the 1928 Amsterdam Games, which marked the debut women's events the Olympics, is the inaugural 100m Olympic champion Betty Robinson. She's known be the Olympic champion who rose fron dead win second title with the US 4x100m relay team, eight years after her first gold.'.

node.text:
The incredible story of the inaugural @olympics 100m champion Betty Robinson goes beyond the individual achievement of a talented track athlete.

She 'rose from the dead' to win a second #Olympics title with the US 4x100m relay team, eight years after her first gold 🥇

Her story, beautifully told and illustrated, in the link in our story 🔗

#athletics #trackandfield #motivationmonday

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by World Athletics on August 09, 2021. May be an illustration of text that says 'Betty Robinson Among the stars of the 1928 Amsterdam Games, which marked the debut women's events the Olympics, is the inaugural 100m Olympic champion Betty Robinson. She's known be the Olympic champion who rose fron dead win second title with the US 4x100m relay team, eight years after her first gold.'.

Photo by World Athletics on August 09, 2021. May be an illustration of text that says 'Returning from her first successful Olympic Games, Robinson had her sights home Olympics scheduled to happen Los Angeles in 1932. But 28 June she decided to to go go on plane tour with cousin as pilot, to distract herself from training. That's when the unthinkable happened.'.

Photo by World Athletics on August 09, 2021. May be an illustration of text that says '"The doctor said if hadn't been such good condition, wouldn't have come of it well as did." During her recuperation she found that she could indeed still run. "Not as fast as| used but fast enough to make a team, she said. "It was really a struggle make the team 1936. Ihad to work overtime," she said. Everything went smoothly for the US relay team.'.

Photo by World Athletics on August 09, 2021. May be a cartoon of text that says '"I wish they [the German women] hadn't dropped the baton... "Helen was the faster. We would have won anyway." They finished in first, with an Olympic gold medal.'.
Photo shared by World Athletics on August 09, 2021 tagging @olympics, and @tokyo2020.

With no action on the track it’s that time again - #SifansDayOff! 

On the final day of action in Tokyo our distance Queen kept busy as per usual. Just a casual skydive, trip on the Titanic, relaxing by the pool and playing some mean sax in the Closing Ceremony 🎷 

Jokes aside, she did actually appear at the Closing Ceremony and we loved seeing our multi medal winner representing athletics. Superstar 🥇🥇🥉
